2. Commonly Used Design Patterns
Overview

Design Patterns are reusable solutions to common software design problems. They improve code reusability, flexibility, maintainability, and scalability.

Design Patterns are mainly classified into:

Creational Patterns
Structural Patterns
Behavioral Patterns
Architectural Patterns


2.1 Creational Patterns

Creational Patterns focus on object creation.

A) Singleton Pattern
Meaning

Ensures that only one object of a class exists.

Java Example
class Database {

    private static Database instance =
            new Database();

    private Database(){}

    public static Database getInstance(){
        return instance;
    }
}
Use Cases
Database connection
Logger
Configuration manager
B) Factory Method Pattern
Meaning

Creates objects without exposing object creation logic.

Java Example
interface Animal {
    void sound();
}

class Dog implements Animal {

    public void sound(){
        System.out.println("Bark");
    }
}
Use Cases
Object creation based on conditions
Framework development
C) Builder Pattern
Meaning

Constructs complex objects step by step.

Java Example
class User {

    String name;

    User(String name){
        this.name = name;
    }
}

class UserBuilder {

    String name;

    UserBuilder setName(String name){
        this.name = name;
        return this;
    }

    User build(){
        return new User(name);
    }
}
Use Cases
Large constructors
Complex object creation


2.2 Structural Patterns

Structural Patterns focus on organizing classes and objects.

A) Adapter Pattern
Meaning

Allows incompatible classes to work together.

Example

Phone charger adapter.

Use Cases
Third-party library integration
B) Decorator Pattern
Meaning

Adds additional functionality dynamically.

Example

Coffee + Milk + Sugar

Use Cases
Feature extension
C) Proxy Pattern
Meaning

Controls access to another object.

Example

ATM → Bank Server

Use Cases
Security
Access control


2.3 Behavioral Patterns

Behavioral Patterns focus on object communication.

A) Observer Pattern
Meaning

One object notifies multiple objects.

Example

YouTube notifications.

Use Cases
Event systems
Notification systems
B) Strategy Pattern
Meaning

Multiple algorithms for one task.

Example

Google Maps route selection.

Use Cases
Payment methods
Sorting algorithms
C) Command Pattern
Meaning

Encapsulates a request as an object.

Example

Remote control.

Use Cases
Undo functionality
Task scheduling


2.4 Architectural Patterns
A) Model View Controller (MVC)
Meaning

Separates application into three parts.

Model → Data
View → User Interface
Controller → Business Logic
Use Cases
Web applications
B) Dependency Injection
Meaning

Dependencies are provided externally instead of creating them internally.

Example

Injecting database services.

Use Cases
Spring Framework
Testable applications
